рЯІ© 3. Enable Caching in Your Application

Add the @EnableCaching annotation to your main Spring Boot application class.

import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;
import org.springframework.cache.annotation.EnableCaching;

@SpringBootApplication
@EnableCaching
public class RedisCacheApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(RedisCacheApplication.class, args);
    }
}

Sure рЯЩВ вАФ hereвАЩs a simple explanation:

### рЯІ© What `@EnableCaching` does:

`@EnableCaching` **turns on SpringвАЩs caching feature** in your application.

### рЯТ° In short:

When you add `@EnableCaching`, Spring will start **looking for methods with caching annotations** (like `@Cacheable`, `@CachePut`, `@CacheEvict`) and automatically handle storing and retrieving data from the cache for you.

### рЯЪА Benefit:

It makes your app **faster** and **more efficient** because:

* Spring will **skip expensive operations** (like database calls) if the result is already cached.
* You donвАЩt have to manually write code to manage the cache вАФ Spring does it for you.

### рЯІ† Example:

Without `@EnableCaching`:
Every time you call `getUserById("123")`, it hits the database.

With `@EnableCaching`:
Spring first checks Redis (the cache).
If user `"123"` is already there вЖТ returns it immediately (no DB call).
If not вЖТ fetches from DB, saves it in Redis, and returns it.

рЯСЙ **In one line:**
`@EnableCaching` activates SpringвАЩs automatic caching system to speed up your app and reduce unnecessary work.


рЯІ† 4. Configure Redis Template (optional but recommended)

If you want to control serialization or handle custom objects, create a configuration class:

import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.data.redis.connection.RedisConnectionFactory;
import org.springframework.data.redis.core.RedisTemplate;
import org.springframework.data.redis.serializer.GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer;
import org.springframework.data.redis.serializer.StringRedisSerializer;

@Configuration
public class RedisConfig {

    @Bean
    public RedisTemplate<String, Object> redisTemplate(RedisConnectionFactory connectionFactory) {
        RedisTemplate<String, Object> template = new RedisTemplate<>();
        template.setConnectionFactory(connectionFactory);

        template.setKeySerializer(new StringRedisSerializer());
        template.setValueSerializer(new GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer());
        template.setHashKeySerializer(new StringRedisSerializer());
        template.setHashValueSerializer(new GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer());

        template.afterPropertiesSet();
        return template;
    }
}

Of course рЯШК hereвАЩs the **super simple** version:

### рЯТ° What this class does:

This class tells Spring **how to talk to Redis**.

### вЪЩпЄП In plain words:

* It **creates a RedisTemplate** вАФ a tool your app uses to read and write data in Redis.
* It says:

  * вАЬрЯФС Store keys as **text** (easy to read).вАЭ
  * вАЬрЯУ¶ Store values as **JSON** (so we can save whole Java objects, not just strings).вАЭ

### рЯІ† Simple meaning:

> This class helps your app **save and read data from Redis in a nice, readable way**, using strings for keys and JSON for data.


if u still dont use this class because its optional : 

Yes рЯСН вАФ it will **still work** even if you donвАЩt use this class.

### рЯТ° HereвАЩs why:

Spring Boot already provides a **default `RedisTemplate`** and **default serializers**, so caching and basic Redis operations will work out of the box.

### рЯІ© ButвА¶ without this class:

* Keys and values might be stored in **binary format** (not readable in Redis CLI).
* Custom Java objects might not be stored or retrieved properly (you could get weird unreadable data or errors).

### вЬЕ So:

* **For simple data** (like strings, numbers): works fine without this class.
* **For complex objects** (like `User`, `Product`, etc.): better to add this config вАФ it makes everything easier and safer.

рЯСЙ **In short:**
It will still work, but adding this class makes Redis data **clearer, more readable, and more reliable** вАФ especially when caching custom objects.


рЯЪА 5. Use Caching in Your Service Layer

You can now use caching annotations:

@Cacheable вАФ caches the result

@CachePut вАФ updates the cache

@CacheEvict вАФ removes from the cache

Example:

import org.springframework.cache.annotation.Cacheable;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
