Q10 : What is transaction in spring boot ?
Transaction in Spring Boot вАУ Simple Explanation

A transaction in Spring Boot means a group of operations that must all succeed or all fail together вАФ just like a 
promise:

вАЬDo everything, or do nothing.вАЭ вЬЕвЭМ

рЯТ° Simple Example:

Imagine you are transferring money between two accounts рЯТЄ

Deduct вВє1000 from Account A

Add вВє1000 to Account B

Both steps must happen together.
If step 2 fails (like a network error), step 1 should be undone вАФ
so no money is lost or duplicated.

ThatвАЩs what a transaction ensures.

вЪЩпЄП How it works in Spring Boot:

In Spring Boot, you can use the @Transactional annotation.

@Service
public class BankService {

    @Transactional
    public void transferMoney() {
        debitFromAccountA();
        creditToAccountB();
    }
}


If any line inside this method fails (throws an exception),
Spring automatically rolls back the transaction вАФ
undoing any database changes made so far.

вЬЕ In short:

A transaction in Spring Boot ensures that multiple database operations act as one unit вАФ
either all succeed or all rollback to keep data safe and consistent.

Q11 : What is 2 phase commit  ? 
Two-Phase Commit (2PC) вАУ Simple Explanation

The Two-Phase Commit is a way to make sure a transaction across multiple databases or services either completes
everywhere or fails everywhere вАФ so all systems stay in sync.

рЯСЙ In simple words:

2PC = Everyone agrees to commit or everyone cancels.
(All or nothing!) 

Real-life Example:

Imagine you are transferring вВє1000 from your Bank A account to Bank B рЯТЄ

Two things must happen:

вВє1000 is deducted from Bank A рЯП¶

вВє1000 is added to Bank B рЯТ∞

Both must succeed вАФ or both must fail.
If one fails (like Bank B is down), the other must rollback (undo) the change.

Q12 : So Transaction and 2 phase commit both are kind of same then what is the difference between them ?
Ans : 
Excellent question рЯСН вАФ and a very common one in interviews!

LetвАЩs make it super simple рЯСЗ

---

### рЯІ† **Difference Between Transaction and Two-Phase Commit (2PC)**

| Feature           | **Transaction**                                              | **Two-Phase Commit (2PC)**                                                        |
| ----------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| рЯТ° **Meaning**    | A **single unit of work** that must fully succeed or fail.   | A **protocol** to coordinate a transaction **across multiple systems/databases**. |
| рЯП¶ **Scope**      | Happens **inside one database** (local).                     | Happens **across multiple databases or services** (distributed).                  |
| вЪЩпЄП **Handled By** | Database or SpringвАЩs `@Transactional` manager.               | A **Transaction Coordinator** that manages all systems.                           |
| рЯФБ **Phases**     | One step вЖТ commit or rollback.                               | Two steps вЖТ **Prepare** and **Commit** (or rollback).                             |
| рЯФТ **Example**    | Transfer money between two accounts in the **same bank DB**. | Transfer money from **Bank A DB** to **Bank B DB** вАФ two separate databases.      |
| рЯІ© **Rollback**   | Simple rollback handled by one DB.                           | Coordinator ensures rollback across all DBs if any one fails.                     |

---

### рЯТђ **Simple way to remember:**

> * **Transaction** = All-or-nothing **inside one system**.
> * **Two-Phase Commit (2PC)** = All-or-nothing **across many systems**.

---

### рЯТ° Example:

* **Transaction:** Deduct and add money between two accounts in **the same database**.
* **2PC:** Deduct money from Bank AвАЩs database and add it to Bank BвАЩs database вЖТ needs coordination between both.

---

### вЬЕ **In short:**

> A **transaction** keeps data consistent **within one system**,
> while a **2-phase commit** keeps data consistent **across multiple systems**.


